text: Wikipedia article of the day A chicken gun is a large diameter  compressed air cannon used to fire dead chickens at aircraft components in order to simulate high speed bird strikes during the aircraft s flight  Jet engines and aircraft windshields are particularly vulnerable to damage from such strikes  and are the most common target in such tests  Whole  dead  standard size chickens  as would be used for cooking  are thought to accurately simulate a large  live bird striking a plane in flight The aircraft component to be tested  engine  windshield  etc  is fixed in place on a test stand  and the cannon fires the chicken at it The chicken gun was first used in the mid s at de Havilland Aircraft  Hatfield  Hertfordshire  The chickens were killed at a local farm shortly before use  Another early use of a chicken gun was by the Royal Aeronautical  Aircraft  Establishment  RAE  in Farnborough  Hampshire in  In the  s  Goodyear Aerospace in Litchfield Park  Arizona  used a gun with a ceramic diaphragm to seal the compressed air at the back of the gun s barrel  To fire the gun  a needle struck and ruptured the diaphragm  allowing the compressed air to drive the chicken  in its container a cylindrical cardboard ice cream carton  down the barrel  At the muzzle  a metal ring stopped the carton  but allowed the chicken to pass through  Cameras recorded the collision The United States Air Force commissioned the AEDC Ballistic Range S  to test airplane canopies  which began operating in  The gun was later used to test other aircraft parts such as the leading edges of wings During the development of the Boeing   in the  s  the cockpit windows were subjected to a  chicken test  where  an anesthetized  pound   kg  chicken was loaded in a pneumatic gun and fired at   knots   mph    km h  head on It is described as  a very messy test
summary: A chicken gun is a large diameter compressed air cannon used to fire dead chickens at aircraft components to simulate bird strikes during the aircraft's flight. It was first used in the mid s at de Havilland Aircraft Hatfield Hertfordshire. Goodyear Aerospace in Arizona used a gun with a ceramic diaphragm to seal the compressed air at the back of the barrel. The United States Air Force commissioned the AEDC Ballistic Range S to test airplane canopies.
cleaned: chicken gun large diameter compress air cannon fire dead chicken aircraft component simulate bird strike aircraft flight mid sit de land aircraft hatfield hertfordshire goodyear aerospace arizona gun ceramic diaphragm seal compress air barrel united states air force commission ballistic range test air lane canopy
